\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "LV3"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:har-cond"

\end_inset

The conductance of Hit-and-Run in a convex body 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 containing the unit ball and of diameter 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega(1/nD)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This implies a mixing time of 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(n^{2}D^{2}\log(M/\varepsilon)\right)$
\end_inset

 to get to within distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 of the target density starting from an 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

-warm initial density.
 By taking one step from the initial point,
 we can bound 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $(D/d)^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is the minimum distance of the starting point from the boundary.
 Hence this gives a bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{O}(n^{3}D^{2})$
\end_inset

 from 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 interior starting point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proof of the theorem follows the same high-level outline as that of the ball walk,
 needing two major ingredients,
 namely,
 one-step coupling and isoperimetry.
 Notably,
 the isoperimetry is for a non-Euclidean notion of distance.
 We begin with some suitable definitions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

median
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 step-size function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 as the 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pr(\norm{x-y}\le F(x))=\frac{1}{8}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a random step from 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also need a non-Euclidean notion of distance,
 namely the classical cross-ratio distance.
 For points 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

,
 inducing a chord 
\begin_inset Formula $[p,q]$
\end_inset

 with these points in the order 
\begin_inset Formula $p,u,v,q$
\end_inset

,
 the cross-ratio distance is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{K}(u,v)=\frac{\norm{u-v}\norm{p-q}}{\norm{p-u}\norm{v-q}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is related to the Hilbert distance (which is a true distance) as follows:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{H}(u,v)=\ln\left(1+d_{K}(u,v)\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first ingredient shows that if two points are close geometrically,
 then their next-step distributions have significant overlap.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:har_one_step"

\end_inset

 For two points 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in K$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{K}(u,v)<\frac{1}{8}\mbox{ and }\norm{u-v}\le\frac{2}{\sqrt{n}}\max\left\{ F(u),F(v)\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

we have 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{TV}(P_{u},P_{v})<1-\frac{1}{500}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second ingredient is an isoperimetric inequality (independent of any algorithm).
 The cross-ratio distance has a nice isoperimetry inequality.
\end_layout

