\begin_layout Section
Dikin walk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both the ball walk and hit-and-run have a dependence on the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

roundness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the target distribution,
 e.g.,
 via its diameter or average distance to the center of gravity.
 Reducing this dependence to logarithmic by rounding is polynomial time but expensive.
 The current best rounding algorithm (which achieves near-isotropic position) has complexity 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{*}(n^{3})$
\end_inset

.
 Here we describe a different approach,
 which is affine-invariant,
 but requires more knowledge of the convex body.
 In particular,
 we will focus on the special case of sampling an explicit polytope 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\left\{ x:\,Ax\ge b\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general Dikin walk is defined as follows.
 For a convex set 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 with a positive definite matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mh(u)$
\end_inset

 for each point 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in K$
\end_inset

 ,
 let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{u}(r)=\left\{ x:\,(x-u)^{\top}\mh(u)(x-u)\le r\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

